The Post-Cold War Order
Cambridge – many analysts believe that the Post-Cold War Order came to an end with China's rise and the election of US President Donald Trump.
But would he then be trying to revive it if Joe Biden were to defeat Trump in the November election?
Perhaps the outcome is not as such, but he must find some alternative options.
Critics argue that the post-1945 US order was neither global nor always very free, which is correct.
It would exclude more than half of the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and incorporate many authoritarian states.
The US hegemony has always been exaggerated.
Despite this, the most powerful countries must lead in creating global public goods, otherwise they will not be provided — and Americans will suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example.
The Biden administration's realistic goal should be to establish a rule-based international system, with different member countries participating in various affairs.
China and Russia, whether they will be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and 2000s, neither country was able to balance the power of the US, while the US unilaterally pursued its commitment to liberal values.
The US bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without the approval of the UN Security Council.
It also supports a 2005 UN General Assembly resolution on "responsibility to protect," intended to provide protection for citizens subjected to brutal treatment by their own governments – an argument later used by the US in 2011 to justify bombing Libya in order to protect civilians in Benghazi.
Critics describe this record as American hubris during the post-Cold War era – for instance, when NATO-led intervention in Libya ultimately led to regime change, Russia and China felt deceived – while defenders of this action describe it as a natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
Regardless, the growth in Chinese and Russian power has more strictly limited freedom of interventionism.
What remains, then?
Russia and China stress the principle of sovereignty as stipulated in the United Nations Charter, which holds that a state can wage war only in self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, instances of occupying a neighboring country's territory by force have been rare, and when they have occurred, they have come at a steep price in the form of sanctions (as with Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
In addition, the Security Council has frequently authorized the deployment of peacekeeping forces in countries in distress, while political cooperation has also successfully curtailed the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This dimension of a rule-based order remains crucial.
Specifically in economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Well before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism had underpinned the unfair mercantilist model, which distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
This would lead to a decoupling of global supply chains, particularly in cases where national security is at risk.
Although China complains that the US is preventing companies like Huawei from building 5G networks in the West, this US stance is consistent with demands for sovereignty.
After all, China has blocked Google, Facebook, and Twitter from operating in the country for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules would help prevent the decoupling from escalating.
Despite the outbreak of this current crisis, cooperation in key financial areas remains extremely robust.
Conversely, mutual dependence in the ecological field poses an insurmountable obstacle in the face of sovereignty, as threats are transboundary.
Despite the setbacks to economic globalization, environmental globalization will continue to unfold, as it is governed by biological and physical laws, which are unaffected by the logic of contemporary geopolitics.
The issues mentioned above threaten everyone, but no country has the capacity to resolve them independently.
In issues like the 2019 COVID-19 pandemic and climate change, power also has a so-called positive and constructive dimension.
Thinking about exercising power over others alone is insufficient under such premises.
We must also think about exercising power in cooperation with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization have been beneficial to us and others.
Since Nixon's meeting with Mao in 1972, despite ideological differences, it has not affected cooperation between China and the US.
Biden's challenge is whether the US and China can cooperate to produce global public goods while engaging in competition in the traditional great power rivalry sphere.
The digital space is a brand-new significant issue — — because it has a partly transnational nature, but is also controlled by sovereign governments.
The digital space has been partially fragmented.
These rules may not be recognized by authoritarian states.
If authoritarian regimes also want to achieve interconnectivity, certain rules prohibiting the alteration of the internet's fundamental structure are also in their interests, just as the Global Commission on the Stability of Cyberspace has recommended.
But when they resort to proxy operations or election interference through information warfare (which violates sovereignty), they must be subject to rules like those that the US and the Soviet Union negotiated during the Cold War to prevent escalations at sea, even as ideological animosity persists.
The US and like-minded nations must publicly declare the rules they intend to uphold and establish the necessary deterrents.
Embracing the free values of cyberspace does not imply unilateral disarmament by the US.
Instead, the US should distinguish between permissible public soft power and clandestine information warfare, allowing for the latter only when necessary to counter such operations when the other side launches them.
Permissible public broadcasting by Russia and China is allowed, but clandestine unified actions such as manipulating social media are not.
And the US will continue to criticize the human rights records of these countries.
Public opinion polls show that the US public wants to avoid military intervention, but does not want to withdraw from alliances or multilateral cooperation.
And the public still treasures values.
If Biden is elected, the issue he faces is not whether to revive the Post-Cold War Order.
The issue at hand is whether the US can collaborate with core allies to promote democracy and human rights while simultaneously working with a broader range of countries to establish a rule-based international system for managing transnational threats such as climate change, pandemics, cyber attacks, terrorism, and economic turbulence.
